# Always provide --dry-run for destructive CLI operations

## Context

Any CLI script that creates, modifies, or deletes files should have a --dry-run flag

## Pattern

Add --dry-run flag that shows exact files to be created/modified/deleted without making changes. Users can preview operations before committing, reducing fear and increasing confidence.

## Example

```typescript
if (args.dryRun) {
  console.log(`Would remove ${files.length} files:`);
  for (const f of files) console.log(`  - DELETE ${f}`);
  process.exit(0);
}
```

## Why

Users hesitate to run commands when they don't know what will change. Dry-run eliminates this friction by providing a safe preview mode.

# Warn about unknown flags instead of failing silently

## Context

CLI argument parsing should detect and warn about unrecognized flags

## Pattern

Track unknown flags during parsing and display a warning with the list of valid flags. Continue execution rather than exiting, so automation isn't broken.

## Example

```typescript
const VALID_FLAGS = new Set(['--help', '--json', '--dry-run']);
if (arg.startsWith('--') && !VALID_FLAGS.has(arg)) {
  args.unknownFlags.push(arg);
}
// Later:
console.log(`⚠ Unknown: ${unknownFlags.join(', ')}`);
console.log(`  Valid: ${[...VALID_FLAGS].join(', ')}`);
```

## Why

Users often typo flags (--with-herald-company vs --herald-company). Silent ignore means they think a feature is enabled when it's not. Immediate warning prevents confusion.
